The files that will be analysed are downloaded and stored collectively in ‘files’. They are then read and the first 5 rows of the first file are printed.

url <- "https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/geo/download/?acc=GSE63310&format=file"
utils::download.file(url, destfile="GSE63310_RAW.tar", mode="wb") 
utils::untar("GSE63310_RAW.tar", exdir = ".")
files <- c("GSM1545535_10_6_5_11.txt", "GSM1545536_9_6_5_11.txt", "GSM1545538_purep53.txt",
  "GSM1545539_JMS8-2.txt", "GSM1545540_JMS8-3.txt", "GSM1545541_JMS8-4.txt",
  "GSM1545542_JMS8-5.txt", "GSM1545544_JMS9-P7c.txt", "GSM1545545_JMS9-P8c.txt")
for(i in paste(files, ".gz", sep=""))
R.utils::gunzip(i, overwrite=TRUE)
files <- c("GSM1545535_10_6_5_11.txt", "GSM1545536_9_6_5_11.txt", 
   "GSM1545538_purep53.txt", "GSM1545539_JMS8-2.txt",

readDGE is a package that allows the files to be grouped into a single matrix collectively.

The data in the columns are arraged according to the experimental parameters. E.g. the cell type(basal, LP and ML), the genotype(wild-type,knockout), the phenotype(disease status, sex, age)

samplenames <- substring(colnames(x), 12, nchar(colnames(x)))
samplenames
## [1] "10_6_5_11" "9_6_5_11"  "purep53"   "JMS8-2"    "JMS8-3"    "JMS8-4"   
## [7] "JMS8-5"    "JMS9-P7c"  "JMS9-P8c"
colnames(x) <- samplenames
group <- as.factor(c("LP", "ML", "Basal", "Basal", "ML", "LP", 
                     "Basal", "ML", "LP"))
x$samples$group <- group
lane <- as.factor(rep(c("L004","L006","L008"), c(3,4,2)))
x$samples$lane <- lane
x$samples

#The data is further organized into a data frame called ‘genes’. The information to form the dataframe is retreived from the loaded package “mus.musculus”. The three columns in the data frame are the gene id, symbol and chromosome.

The data is then pre-processed. CPM stands for counts per million. If we have a library of genes that is approximately 20 million base pairs, a cpm value of 1 would indicate that there are 20 counts within the sample. Log-cpm is used for exploratory plots. edgeR offers the calculation of cpm and lcpm using built-in functions.

cpm <- cpm(x)
lcpm <- cpm(x, log=TRUE)
L <- mean(x$samples$lib.size) * 1e-6
M <- median(x$samples$lib.size) * 1e-6
c(L, M)
## [1] 45.48855 51.36862

#The data is then normalized. This is performed using a built-in function in calcNorm. The effects or normalizing are studied by inflating one set of data and reducing another and analysing the changes.

x <- calcNormFactors(x, method = "TMM")
x$samples$norm.factors
## [1] 0.8943956 1.0250186 1.0459005 1.0458455 1.0162707 0.9217132 0.9961959
## [8] 1.0861026 0.9839203
x2 <- x
x2$samples$norm.factors <- 1
x2$counts[,1] <- ceiling(x2$counts[,1]*0.05)
x2$counts[,2] <- x2$counts[,2]*5
par(mfrow=c(1,2))
lcpm <- cpm(x2, log=TRUE)
boxplot(lcpm, las=2, col=col, main="")
title(main="A. Example: Unnormalised data",ylab="Log-cpm")
x2 <- calcNormFactors(x2)

x2$samples$norm.factors
## [1] 0.05770899 6.08287835 1.22023972 1.16478991 1.19661094 1.04659233
## [7] 1.15048074 1.25431164 1.10901983
lcpm <- cpm(x2, log=TRUE)
boxplot(lcpm, las=2, col=col, main="")
title(main="B. Example: Normalised data",ylab="Log-cpm")

#The samples are clustered. An MDS polt allows us to visulize what factor impacts the data the greatest. Other factors would fall farther from that factor.

lcpm <- cpm(x, log=TRUE)
par(mfrow=c(1,2))
col.group <- group
levels(col.group) <-  brewer.pal(nlevels(col.group), "Set1")
col.group <- as.character(col.group)
col.lane <- lane
levels(col.lane) <-  brewer.pal(nlevels(col.lane), "Set2")
col.lane <- as.character(col.lane)
plotMDS(lcpm, labels=group, col=col.group)
title(main="A. Sample groups")
plotMDS(lcpm, labels=lane, col=col.lane, dim=c(3,4))
title(main="B. Sequencing lanes")

glMDSPlot(lcpm, labels=paste(group, lane, sep="_"), 
          groups=x$samples[,c(2,5)], launch=TRUE)

vfit <- lmFit(v, design)
vfit <- contrasts.fit(vfit, contrasts=contr.matrix)
efit <- eBayes(vfit)
plotSA(efit, main="Final model: Mean-variance trend")

library(limma)
summary(decideTests(efit))
##        BasalvsLP BasalvsML LPvsML
